{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530033"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:01:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:01:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14483"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14483"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.1,0.32,0.08,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97504"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7178"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14483"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80100"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1085"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4656"},{"type":"tags","id":"4807"},{"type":"tags","id":"4824"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17246"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17791"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33402"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97504"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of joint pain and swelling. She also reports having eye irritation and a slight rash during the same time. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is sexually active with a new partner for the past two months and reports having dyspareunia and intermittent dysuria for the past four weeks. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Her right knee and left wrist are swollen, warm, and tender. Bilateral conjunctival injection is noted. A rash consisting of small, painless, reddish-brown raised lesions is visible on her palms and soles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn arthrocentesis of the knee is conducted, and is culture negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Midstream urine nucleic acid amplification test","Blood cultures","First pass urine nucleic acid amplification test","Urine microscopy, sensitivity and cultures","Endocervical nucleic acid amplification test"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a clinical picture suggestive of reactive arthritis, also known as Reiter\u0027s syndrome. The classic triad of symptoms includes arthritis, conjunctivitis, and urethritis (or cervicitis in women), often accompanied by characteristic skin lesions. The skin lesions described are small, painless, reddish-brown raised lesions on the palms and soles, and are known as keratoderma blenorrhagicum, which is a characteristic rash seen in reactive arthritis. Reactive arthritis symptoms typically develop 1-4 weeks after a wide variety of triggering infections such as gastroenteritis (\u003Cem\u003Ecampylobacter, shigella, salmonella\u003C/em\u003E), cystitis (\u003Cem\u003EE. coli)\u003C/em\u003E and in this case, sexually transmitted infections (most likely \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis \u003C/em\u003Einfection in this case but can also be caused by \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E)\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C/em\u003E Note that the synovial fluid is sterile in reactive arthritis, as the inflammation is due to cross-reactivity of chlamydia antigens with joint tissues. Patients with reactive arthritis are sometimes described as having the following issues: \u0022can\u0027t see, can\u0027t pee, can\u0027t climb a tree,\u0022 which refers to conjunctivitis (can\u0027t see), urethritis (can\u0027t pee), and arthritis (can\u0027t climb a tree).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndocervical nucleic acid amplification test\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate diagnostic test for detecting \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E in women with suspected reactive arthritis. This test offers superior sensitivity (\u0026gt;95%) and specificity (\u0026gt;99%) compared to other methods. Australian STI management guidelines specifically recommend endocervical swabs as the preferred specimen when performing a speculum examination in people with a cervix with suspected chlamydial infection, particularly when there are symptoms suggesting cervicitis or pelvic inflammatory disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMidstream urine nucleic acid amplification test\u003C/strong\u003E is not the preferred method for detecting chlamydial infections in people with a cervix, as it may not be as sensitive as endocervical swabs. It is more commonly used in people with a penis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E are typically performed when there\u0027s suspicion of bacteraemia or sepsis. While this patient has a fever, her overall presentation is more consistent with reactive arthritis rather than systemic infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst pass urine nucleic acid amplification test\u003C/strong\u003E is a valid option for detecting chlamydial infections, particularly penile urethritis. However, in symptomatic people with a cervix, endocervical swabs are generally more reliable and are the recommended site of testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine microscopy, cultures, and sensitivity \u003C/strong\u003Eis not useful for diagnosing chlamydial infections, as \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E does not grow in standard bacterial cultures. It is more appropriate for diagnosing urinary tract infections caused by other bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENote that, after confirming the underlying chlamydial infection with NAAT, the appropriate treatment for a non-pregnant adult is doxycycline 100 mg twice daily for 7 days. It\u0027s also important to screen and treat sexual partners to prevent reinfection and further transmission. The patient should be counselled on safe sex practices and the importance of consistent condom use. Management of reactive arthritis may also include NSAIDs for symptomatic relief and, in some cases, referral to a rheumatologist for further evaluation and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Reactive arthritis typically presents with the triad of arthritis, conjunctivitis, and urethritis, often 1-4 weeks after a chlamydial infection.","Nucleic acid amplification testing (NAAT) of urine or genital swabs is the preferred diagnostic method for identifying the underlying chlamydial infection in reactive arthritis.","Doxycycline is the first-line treatment for the underlying chlamydial infection in non-pregnant adults with reactive arthritis."],"references":["Australasian Society for HIV, Viral Hepatitis and Sexual Health Medicine. Chlamydia. STI Guidelines Australia. 2024. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/chlamydia/","Lahu A, Backa T, Ismaili J, Lahu V, Saiti V. Modes of presentation of reactive arthritis based on the affected joints. Med Arch. 2015 Feb;69(1):42-5. doi: 10.5455/medarh.2015.69.42-45. Epub 2015 Feb 21. PMID: 25870477; PMCID: PMC4384843. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4384843/","Barth WF, Segal K. Reactive Arthritis (Reiter\u2019s Syndrome). American Family Physician [Internet]. 1999 Aug 1;60(2):499\u2013503. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/1999/0801/p499.html","Coelho I, Costa S, Mendes SS, Gomes GC. Keratoderma blennorrhagica. BMJ Case Rep. 2017 Nov 16;2017:bcr2017222475. doi: 10.1136/bcr-2017-222475. PMID: 29146729; PMCID: PMC5699121."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14483"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80100"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-07T14:19:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-07T14:20:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7178"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97504"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta